<preface>
<title>Epigrams</title>
<blockquote>
<p>  
  I cannot but see a stark contradiction between the intuitively clear
  fundamental formulas of the integral calculus and the incomparably
  artificial and complex work of their "justification" and their
  "proofs". One must be quite stupid not to see this at once, and
  quite careless if, after having seen this, one can get used to this
  artificial, logical atmosphere, and can later on forget this stark
  contradiction.
</p>
<p>
-- <url href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Luzin/" visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Luzin/">Nikolai Nikolaievich Luzin</url>, (1883-1950)
</p>
</blockquote>
</preface>


  
